                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d153">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.008 North Pacific/305: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-03-16T19:00:00+09:00"
                            >March 16, 1938—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 16—7:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>174. Department’s 90, March 15, 6 p.m.—Alaska fisheries.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>In reply to an inquiry which we made today, Yoshizawa stated that there is
                        no basis whatever for the Associated Press story. He added that the Japanese
                        Government not only has <hi rend="italic">no</hi> intention of reopening the
                        negotiations but that it looks forward to publication at an early date of a
                        press communiqué acceptable to both Governments.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>The Associated Press correspondent declines to disclose to us the source
                        of his story.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
